Subject: [PATCH 2/6] Auto-apply Linux transparency flags when compositor is absent

Pet mode relies on `transparent: true` BrowserWindow. On Linux this only
works when a compositor is running (mutter / kwin / picom / wayfire /
river, etc.). Without one, electron falls back to an opaque black
background — the mascot appears inside a black rectangle.

Chromium fixes this when launched with:

  --enable-transparent-visuals --disable-gpu-compositing

but these must be appended via `app.commandLine.appendSwitch` BEFORE
`app.whenReady()` resolves. Upstream does not do this, because on
Windows/macOS the flags are unnecessary and on Linux they assume a
compositor is present.

This patch adds a small probe (read $XDG_SESSION_TYPE / look for a
compositor socket) in `src/main/index.ts` and conditionally appends
the two switches on Linux when the probe fails. On Wayland sessions
the flags are harmless; on X11 without a compositor they are
load-bearing.

Applies against: vendor/open-llm-vtuber-web @ d176e7df2366952e3bacbf12cf9a8b18a4315932

